The structures and morphologies of AuNPs/Thi/MSNP-NH2 were characterized by SEM and EDS. As shown in Fig. 2
                        , a great amount of filamentous MSNP-NH2 with a diameter of approximately 30 nm was, which shows a uniform surface topography and a mesh structure. After HAuCl4 reduction by NaBH4, clear AuNPs particles (15 ± 2 nm) were observed on the surface of the MSNP-NH2, which not only provide an efficient electrode surface for loading Ab2 through thionin linking but also promote the electron transfer during electrochemical detection (Fig. 3
                        ).

To examine the potential practical applications of the immunosensor, different concentrations of CA 15–3 were spiked into human serum samples (Fig. 9
                           ). The human plasma samples were not processed. Then, the calibration curved was obtained. As summarized in Table 2
                           , the recovery rates of the four concentrations in serum samples were observed in the range from 92% to 115.8% and the relative standard deviation (RSD) (n = 3) was less than 5.4%, suggesting the acceptable reliability and accuracy of the fabricated immunosensor.
